outcomes.title: Sampling and Data
outcomes.description: I understand different sampling methods and the types of data collected.
outcomes.template:
Scenario:

A recent poll by Quinnipiac University asked U.S. adults about their opinions of President Biden. {{sample_phrase}} The pollsters spoke to {{sample}} U.S. adults out of 2750 that they tried to reach from November 3rd - 6th, 2023. Of the poll participants, {{result}}\% {{outcome}}

What is the population that this study is trying to get information about?

U.S. adults

What is the sample?

The {{sample}} U.S. adults polled.

What is the variable used for this study?

Does a U.S. adult {{outcome}}

What type of variable is the variable in question 3?

Categorical

What is the sample statistic for this study?

The sample statistic is {{result}}\% of those polled {{outcome}}

What is the parameter of interest for this study? (the population parameter that the pollsters are trying to gather information about)

The parameter of interest is what percentage of U.S. adults {{outcome}}

outcomes.description: I Understand different types of experimental design and the possible resulting bias.
outcomes.template:
Scenario:

The US Army wants to get an idea of how Americans feel about the current conflict in Ukraine. In order to get the information, the Army partnered with Quinnipiac University to randomly send a survey to 950 Army Officers living at Fort Bragg. Survey respondents completed the survey online using a code provided in the invitation. The survey was available in English.

Survey respondents were asked to decide to what degree they agreed with the following statements. The possible answer were "Strongly Agree", "Agree", "Neither Agree or Disagree", "Disagree", "Strongly Disagree".

Russia needs to be punished for its evil actions taken to completely destroy the lives of Ukrainian citizens.

The people responsible for the US military response to the conflict are extremely cowardly not to put the extraordinary US military in the field against the Russians.

{{sample}} Officers responded to the survey. {{result_1}}\% of respondents said that they {{agree_1}} that Russia needs to be punished for its evil actions taken to completely destroy the lives of Ukrainian citizens and {{result_2}}\% said that they {{agree_2}} that the people responsible for the US military response to the conflict are extremely cowardly not to put the extraordinary US military in the field against the Russians.

Does the above use a sampling frame? If so, what is the sampling frame?

Yes, Army Officers at Fort Bragg

What is the sampling method used in the above scenario?

The sampling method was a simple random sample or SRS

Looking at the sampling frame and the sampling method, would the sample be a valid sample or is it likely to be a biased sample? Explain why.

The sample frame is likely to produce a biased sample

Identify potential sources of bias other than the sampling method from the information given and explain why they lead to bias (Only use the information given, do not speculate about information not provided).

The wording of the statements (it is ok if a student says only one language although all US Officers must know English).

If the US Army did the survey again, would you expect that exactly {{result_1}}\% of respondents would {{agree_1}} that Russia needs to be punished for its evil actions taken to completely destroy the lives of Ukrainian citizens? Why or why not?

No, the exact same result would not be expected due to natural variability

Based on the results of this survey, can the US Army be sure they have a good idea of how Americans feel about the current conflict in Ukraine? Why or why not?

No, too much bias

outcomes.title: Graphical Illustrations of Data
outcomes.description: I Understand the meaning, benefits, and drawbacks of graphs for qualitative and quantitative data.
outcomes.template:
A critical component to our understanding of statistics is being able to read and understand graphs. It is also critical that we be able to look at graphs and identify any flaws they might have. Be sure to answer ALL the questions.

Share of ransomware attacks by industry type.

Use the graph above to answer the questions.

What type of graph is this?

bar graph

Could you use a {{graph_2}} graph to display this data? Why or why not?

{{answer_2}}

What does the number at the end of the bar in the {{industry_3}} line mean in the context of the information presented by the graph?

{{answer_3}}% of ransomware attacks from July 2020 to June 2021, were made against companies in the {{industry_3}} industry.

If we assume that the total number of ransomware attacks that occured between July 2020 and June 2021 was {{attack_4}}, how many attacks were there against companies in the {{industry_4}} sector? Show all your work and explain how you arrived at your answer.

{{answer_4}}
